2026-04-21 01:28:02 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['timing potentiometer in control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='The system shows a strictly periodic interruption of the lamp (about every 20 s, ~0.5 s off) that is unaffected by ambient light or by the sensitivity setting. The relay is confirmed closed and both lamps are lit, meaning supply, load module, and relay contacts are functional during the on state.\n\nWhen the timing potentiometer was swept, the circuit became unstable / failed to converge at the 0.00 setting, indicating that this component strongly affects the control dynamics and that its behavior is abnormal at certain positions. The persistent, regular cycling independent of the light sensor strongly suggests that the timing RC network is malfunctioning—most plausibly the timing potentiometer itself (e.g., internal intermittency, wiper contact issue, or incorrect value)—causing the control circuit to periodically drop the relay drive for a short interval.\n\nNo other component tested so far (sensor, relay, lamps, wiring) shows abnormal behavior, and the fault signature maps directly onto the function of the timing potentiometer. Therefore the most likely root cause is a faulty timing potentiometer in the control module. Replacing this potentiometer should eliminate the unwanted 20 s cycling and allow normal adjustment of on/off timing without oscillations.'
